Whether Gildas himself knew Greek will be considered elsewhere, and on other grounds; at present, we simply dwell upon facts which certainly seem to warn us against founding any argument whatever as to a supposed study of the Greek tongue, and acquaintance with it in the monasteries of Britain, upon the peculiarities of Old Testament quotations found in this book. Gildas simply wrote his Latin of Job, Ezekiel, or Amos, just as he found it in the codices of his time. The close resemblance of this to the ancient Greek version, as the marked agreement of Ranke's fragment shows, cannot be due to Gildas; it just proves how extremely old some parts of the Bible used in Britain must have been, but can prove no more.
